Feb. 15, 1764: The City of St. Louis
was founded by Pierre Laclede Liguest.
May 20, 1770: The Spanish gover nment officially
assumed control of the Territory of Louisiana.
April 30, 1803: The Louisiana Purchase was signed in Paris.
May 14, 1804: The Lewis and Clark
Expedition set out from St. Louis.
March 3, 1805: The Territory of Louisiana
was established. J ames Wilkinson became
the first governor of the territory.
J an. 8, 1818: The first petition was presented
to congress from Missouri requesting statehood.
1820: The Missouri Compromise allowed Missouri to enter
the Union as a slave state and Maine as a free state, keeping
an equal balance between slave and free states.
J uly 19, 1820: Missouri’s first Constitution was adopted.
Aug. 28, 1820: Missouri’s first state elections were held.
Alexander McNair was elected Missouri’s first governor.
Aug. 10, 1821: Missouri was admitted as the 24th U.S. state
by President J ames Monroe. The state capitol was located
in St. Charles until a permanent location was chosen.
J an. 11, 1822: A bill was adopted
to create the Missouri State Seal.
1826: J efferson City was designated as
Missouri’s permanent seat of government.
Nov. 15, 1837: Missouri’s first capitol building
in J efferson City was destroyed by a fire.
April 14, 1841: The University of Missouri, the first
state university west of the Mississippi River, opened.
1849: St. Louis, Independence, Westport and St. J oseph
became points of departure for emigrants bound for
California, making Missouri the "Gateway to the West."
March 6, 1857: The Dred Scott decision was handed down by
U.S. Chief J ustice Roger B. Taney. The case originated in St. Louis.
Under Missouri statutes in 1846, Scott was allowed to sue for his freedom
from slavery because he had lived in Wisconsin, a free territory, before
returning to the slave state of Missouri.
J an. 11, 1865: Slavery was abolished in Missouri
by an ordinance of immediate emancipation. Missouri
was the first slave state to emancipate enslaved people
before the adoption of the 13th Amendment
to the U.S. Constitution.
Sept. 9, 1901: The first State
Fair held in Sedalia opened.
April 30, 1904: The 1904
World’s Fair opened in St. Louis.
1850 1900 1950 2000
1673: Father J acques Marquette and Louis J oliet were the first
Europeans to set foot on land that would later become Missouri.
Feb. 5, 1911: The Missouri State Capitol was completely
destroyed by fire after being struck by lightning
J uly 2, 1919: Missouri became the eleventh
state to ratify the Nineteenth Amendment
granting suffrage to women.
Aug. 4, 1921: The Centennial Road Law,
providing for the construction of a
modern system of Missouri highways,
was signed into law.
Nov. 7, 1922: Mellcene T. Smith and Sarah Lucille Turner
became the first women elected to the Missouri state legislature.
Dec. 12, 1938: The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in the
absence of an equal law school for Black students,
Lloyd Gaines should be admitted to the MU law school.
March 5, 1946: British Prime Minister Winston Churchill delivered
his "Iron Curtain" speech at Westminster College in Fulton.
1965: Construction of the Gateway Arch, designed by
Eero Saarinen, was completed on the original settlement
site of St. Louis. It symbolized the role of St. Louis in the
development of the western frontier.
April 1968: Riots took place in K ansas City in response
to the assassination of Dr. Martin Luther K ing J r.
1977: Gwen B. Giles became Missouri’s first
African American woman state senator.
1993: The Great Flood of 1993 devastated
parts of Missouri and the Midwest.
May 22, 2011: An EF-5 scale tornado
destroyed one-third of J oplin, killing as many
as 158 people with eight indirect deaths.
April 6, 1866: Lincoln Institute, later
Lincoln University, was incorporated as an
institution for Black students in Missouri.
April 9, 1682: Explorer Robert Cavalier, Sieur de La Salle
took possession of the Louisiana Territory area for France.
1250: Earliest Oneota Indegenous people
known to have inhabited ancestral Missouri.
A painting by Fr ank Nuder scher for
Boatman’s Bank in St. Louis shows Laclede
and Chouteau landing in St. Louis in 1763.

J uly 4, 1851: Groundbreaking ceremonies for the construction
of the Pacific Railroad were held in St. Louis. The line was to go
from St. Louis to J efferson City and then to some point on the
western boundary.

Oct. 1, 1812: The first general assembly of the Territory of
Missouri met. The five original counties were organized: Cape
Girardeau, New Madrid, St. Charles, St. Louis and Ste. Genevieve.
